<subSubSection id="E93E6536A69E83D12131B48A37F48219" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8E3CCA1C695470F0A2B4A0C00BAE84FC" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C5B468092E833E5EE2B77A05D676D861" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
A characteristic body pattern allows an easy recognition of this species; the abdomen is light with dark margins and a dark streak or central patch (Figs 
<figureCitation id="AB508A0FFB7C8D99F7E00A757A9CEA6D" captionStart="Figures 75–80" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 80. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., male, habitus 75 ventral view 76 - 80 dorsal view (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures75-80" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427066" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">78</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="102711EFCFAB2DA55C9A1C6EBA9F139D" captionStart="Figures 81–85" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figures 81 - 85. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., female, 81 - 84 habitus, dorsal view 85 epigyne (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures81-85" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427067" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">81</figureCitation>
). Some specimens, probably young adult females (soon after moulting), can be uniformly black and resemble females of 
<taxonomicName id="3866EEA25E1A2AAC48469C930879E4B4" genus="P." lsidName="P. flavipes" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis id="074415BCDCB8EF4E2B7CAB5943951AF2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">P. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but they are distinguishable in having dark palps (that are yellow in the latter species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7ACB28DE971BBB687D526D50CA01DBCA" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="81F02F3C80273B6DB320556C4799DD5E" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E60AF2DF9B2BAD0ECE336F35C469D57" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The specific name is Latin and means 
<emphasis id="38FA3860EFC38E889CB31DC5587DF286" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">decorated</emphasis>
, which refers to the characteristic colour pattern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5F0A5E174F34F60CF4F819C297FCAF2F" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="description">
<paragraph id="7B91AA7901CB050D4D94C4C8338263DD" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E2A9D1B210C552DC963927A0C002F656" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="B06A941EFFB74C0952ECD03521DAD188" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Male.</emphasis>
Measurements. Cephalothorax: length 1.2-1.7, width 1.5-1.8, height 0.5-0.6. Eye field: length 0.8-1.0, anterior width 1.1-1.4, posterior width 1.5-1.8. Abdomen: length 1.7-2.3, width 1.8-2.4.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8DEC972304ED353384D507DD01DF895A" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
General appearance as in Figs 
<figureCitation id="E8391C7D7FBB28122EF97C98A1376BB5" captionStart="Figures 75–80" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 80. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., male, habitus 75 ventral view 76 - 80 dorsal view (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures75-80" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427066" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">75-80</figureCitation>
. Body flat, integument strongly sclerotised, clearly pitted. Carapace wider than long, eye field trapezoid (distance between anterior lateral eyes shorter than between posterior laterals), occupies about half of carapace. Colouration of carapace brown, black around eyes, in some specimens with two large yellowish patches in eye field (Figs 
<figureCitation id="864DE81FF0619636DB7C5C77A05F9E37" captionStart="Figures 75–80" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 80. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., male, habitus 75 ventral view 76 - 80 dorsal view (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures75-80" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427066" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">76</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="347ED4E3C06F2710A36FD6AACCDA1668" captionStart="Figures 75–80" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 80. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., male, habitus 75 ventral view 76 - 80 dorsal view (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures75-80" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427066" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">78</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="ECE490B65DD01920C06E31D73057F056" captionStart="Figures 75–80" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 80. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., male, habitus 75 ventral view 76 - 80 dorsal view (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures75-80" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427066" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">80</figureCitation>
). Dense bristles at eyes of first row and at lateral edges of carapace. Chelicera with three short teeth on promargin and saw-shaped tooth with four tips on retromargin. Labium and endites brownish with lighter tips, sternum rounded, brown. Abdomen very flat, triangular to heart-shaped, wider than long, its anterior margin almost straight. Colouration of abdomen yellow, brown on the edges, with brown longitudinal median streak (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7D9EB90285EFA87B9C702BB46B5A65F5" captionStart="Figures 75–80" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 80. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., male, habitus 75 ventral view 76 - 80 dorsal view (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures75-80" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427066" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">77</figureCitation>
), which is reduced to round patch positioned centrally in some specimens (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2F09186221965F04A99E221ADCA9EFB7" captionStart="Figures 75–80" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 80. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., male, habitus 75 ventral view 76 - 80 dorsal view (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures75-80" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427066" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">79</figureCitation>
). Variation of pattern as presented in Figs 
<figureCitation id="554E1708BD729CEF091799F6361AE51A" captionStart="Figures 75–80" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 80. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., male, habitus 75 ventral view 76 - 80 dorsal view (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures75-80" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427066" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">76-80</figureCitation>
. Abdomen with typical ventral scuta (Figs 
<figureCitation id="09CE87517E6F1A812CE414DAE6724A3F" captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Some morphological characters of Pachyballus and Peplometus 1 Pach. flavipes (specimen from Gabon), male, ventral abdominal scuta 2 Pach. ornatus (specimen from Tanzania), female, ventral abdominal scuta 3 Pach. flavipes (specimen from Congo), embolus 4 Pepl. biscutellatus (specimen from Ivory Coast), palpal organ in ventral view 5 Pach. flavipes (specimen from Zimbabwe), epigyne with broken embolus in copulatory opening 6 Pach. castaneus, pitted integument of abdomen." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427052" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="825CD8696C4B9E282E98CA132F7755B9" captionStart="Figures 75–80" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 75 - 80. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., male, habitus 75 ventral view 76 - 80 dorsal view (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures75-80" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427066" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">75</figureCitation>
). Spinnerets yellow. First pair of legs slightly stouter than other legs, femora enlarged, tibiae slightly thickened, brown, only tarsi light. Other legs yellowish to light brown, femora darker. Palps as in Figs 
<figureCitation id="9D4B61001013A449894BC47BD672A024" captionStart="Figures 86–91" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figures 86 - 91. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., copulatory organs 86 palpal organ, ventral view 87 palpal organ, lateral view 88 - 91 epigyne (89, 91 black form 89, 90 specimens from Usambara Mts)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures86-91" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427068" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">86</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="42BFE47AAF6A406842F71A7F1CA8DD3F" captionStart="Figures 86–91" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figures 86 - 91. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., copulatory organs 86 palpal organ, ventral view 87 palpal organ, lateral view 88 - 91 epigyne (89, 91 black form 89, 90 specimens from Usambara Mts)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures86-91" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427068" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">87</figureCitation>
, embolic coil low, but basal loop high.
</paragraph>
<caption id="810A95CCD047BE365C4CC5F678514DA7" doi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures81-85" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427067" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" start="Figures 81–85" startId="F16">
<paragraph id="2CC1AD10E0CF1196566B71FC14A67487" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="688C27644F0D0D8506DF704EDB19AB25" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Figures 81-85.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="5EEEF07FA7D2F64D2AC5702DB8E02438" authorityName="Wesołowska &amp; Azarkina &amp; Wiśniewski" authorityYear="2020" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Pachyballus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pachyballus ornatus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatus">
<emphasis id="7A217B48B4485F8C019ECDF172CDFC25" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Pachyballus ornatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., female, 
<emphasis id="48C9C534E474429EB9493DF2DBD2A7CD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">81-84</emphasis>
habitus, dorsal view 
<emphasis id="E677946AEFA0596618BB9F2A8B898F33" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">85</emphasis>
epigyne (all specimens from Tanzania).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="B023700007E28B6DC03CF5095E03BE6F" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="0444928B1976A139B2782A93A9CA64AD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Female.</emphasis>
Measurements. Cephalothorax: length 1.3-1.5, width 1.4-1.8, height 0.5-0.6. Eye field: length 0.6-0.8, anterior width 1.1-1.2, posterior width 1.4-1.5. Abdomen: length1.9-2.1, width 2.0-2.2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A3A98048C4F283F71923E7D2D6D162E8" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
General appearance as in Figs 
<figureCitation id="B74E18B29B12169974995B70F992DE74" captionStart="Figures 81–85" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figures 81 - 85. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., female, 81 - 84 habitus, dorsal view 85 epigyne (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures81-85" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427067" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">81-84</figureCitation>
. Body shape and colouration similar to that in male. First legs not enlarged. Palps dark. Epigyne with anterior semi-circular depression divided by a median septum (Figs 
<figureCitation id="BB9A4D484F57677EA1DAF90524FED1ED" captionStart="Figures 86–91" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figures 86 - 91. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., copulatory organs 86 palpal organ, ventral view 87 palpal organ, lateral view 88 - 91 epigyne (89, 91 black form 89, 90 specimens from Usambara Mts)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures86-91" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427068" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">88-91</figureCitation>
). Copulatory ducts very long, form several loose loops, spermathecae oval (Figs 
<figureCitation id="3C11F38353305BE6F973B13B157A31FE" captionStart="Figures 92–97" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figures 92 - 97. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., internal structure of epigyne 92, 94, 95, 97 ventral view, 93, 96 dorsal view (specimens 94 - 96 from Usambara Mts, lower row - black form)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures92-97" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427069" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">92-97</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D3EA1864168F00E3A779DD3D1679A9DC" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="5908F41B1E1BBFB2A1A7132CEB7EE957" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="704B1C9F3A68CD844E3B5D841490FCE1" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
Tanzania and Congo D.R. (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0B3EDE4D6ED551370334DBA5FD662DFA" captionStart="Figures 193–198" captionStartId="F36" captionText="Figures 193 - 198. Distribution maps of Pachyballus and Peplometus species. 193 circle - Pachyballus caelestis, square - P. castaneus, triangle - P. variegatus 194 P. flavipes 195 circle - P. miniscutulus, square - P. mombasensis, triangle - P. ornatus 196 P. transversus 197 circle - Peplometus biscutellatus, square - P. chlorophthalmus 198 circle - P. nimba, square - P. oyo, triangle - P. congoensis." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures193-198" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427088" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">195</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="788AB1D7820BE38A02FAA5F085DB78C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="C1BC9F21C53540B580A1EC31D96DB9D2" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0A45FCCD5A6E3C948342A93CBAD75555" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
Some specimens, probably young females (soon after the moulting), were dark, almost black (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="84C3649D25F84CAC3530F2FE40113F52" captionStart="Figures 81–85" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figures 81 - 85. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., female, 81 - 84 habitus, dorsal view 85 epigyne (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures81-85" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427067" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">84</figureCitation>
). They appear to become brighter with age due to guanine accumulation (light spots are formed by guanine crystals stored under integument). Black females were collected together with light specimens. Internal structure of epigynes similar in light, Figs 
<figureCitation id="5CF1E4E9A14145CA48EFE2677A35FA79" captionStart="Figures 92–97" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figures 92 - 97. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., internal structure of epigyne 92, 94, 95, 97 ventral view, 93, 96 dorsal view (specimens 94 - 96 from Usambara Mts, lower row - black form)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures92-97" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427069" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">92-94</figureCitation>
, and black, Figs 
<figureCitation id="A5DC6FC9F9C63D04A3344AE4AC2359C0" captionStart="Figures 81–85" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figures 81 - 85. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., female, 81 - 84 habitus, dorsal view 85 epigyne (all specimens from Tanzania)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures81-85" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427067" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">85</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="F53248C14151D6506669FD5C81E18EEA" captionStart="Figures 92–97" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figures 92 - 97. Pachyballus ornatus sp. nov., internal structure of epigyne 92, 94, 95, 97 ventral view, 93, 96 dorsal view (specimens 94 - 96 from Usambara Mts, lower row - black form)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures92-97" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427069" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">95-97</figureCitation>
specimens. Colouration seems to turn brighter in the course of life also in males.
</paragraph>
